 2. Basic Commands
- echo â€” Outputs any text or variable provided.  
- whoami â€” Displays the username of the currently logged-in user.

 3. Navigating the Filesystem
- ls â€” Lists all directories and files in the current location.  
- cd â€” Changes directories; used to move between folders or return to the home directory.  
- pwd â€” Prints the full path of the current working directory.  
- cat â€” Displays the content of a file directly in the terminal.

 4. Searching for Files and Data
- find â€” Searches for files by name or pattern.  
  Example: `find / -name "*.txt"` finds all files ending with `.txt`.  
- grep â€” Searches for specific text or patterns within files.  
- wc -l access.log â€” Counts the number of lines (entries) inside `access.log`.

 5. Shell Operators
- & â€” Executes a command in the background.  
- && â€” Chains multiple commands (runs the next only if the previous succeeds).  
- > â€” Redirects command output to a file, overwriting its contents.  
- >> â€” Appends command output to the end of a file instead of overwriting it.

